eb?topicID=209.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Future Space Power</span><hr size=1> My last little essay reffers primarily to the trouble of dealing with large structures on spacecraft... Anyway:<br>
<br>
For a &quot;JIMO to Saturn&quot; mission, where the energy reaching Saturn is about 1.4W/ft^2, you would need a collector about 550 feet wide (circular) to put out 100 Kilowatts (electric) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>... two American football fields wide...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> 100kWe seems a reasonable figure to power a quartet of NEXIS or HiPEP engines and serious science gear. The first big fruits of the Prometheous project will probably be a 100kWe class reactor.<br>
<br>
All the old &quot;Pre Prometheous&quot; reactors all featured thermoionic or thermoelectric converters, which could give you about 5-6% efficency. Not bad if you just need modest power, but today with a Brayton cycle converter, efficencies on the order of 25-35% are easily attainable in a flight-weight system. The SAFE-400 reactor (not SNAP-100) is a design being played around with that achieves a specific power (electric, not thermal) of around ~0.7kWe/Kg, and could probably be improved by raising the reactor temperature. Now, with the higher the temperature, the more efficent the radiators become. The moderate temperature Russian Topaz reactors have no radiators at all hardly, just coolant pipes on the outside of the converter housing. Short radiators might be needed, but nothing huge or fancy that would weigh the system down. Specific energy for a refined nuclear system system is probably around 0.7-0.8kWe/Kg.<br>
<br>
Now about some of the non-energy related issues with a great big collector...<br>
<br>
How are you going to point this huge dish at the Sun when the probe is maneuvering? And maneuver you will, since the mission would be to hop from moon orbit to moon orbit, requiring alot of different thrust angles. You will need to thrust in the direction of the Sun and away so you can get there quickly and slow down, a nearly 180 degree swing. A dish that size would also begin to have non-negligible light pressure, which may introduce attitude control issues. Plus, simply having a substantial mass (&gt;100lbs) at a long distance from the craft (300ft or so) may introduce torque concerns requiring a heavier support structure and more maneuvering thrusters. And, of course, the cells themselves will not last in a high radiation environment; for example the &quot;radioactive death belt&quot; around Jupiter.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>If you can keep the thing pointed at the Sun at all</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Even better, such a large and conductive structure will interfere with sensitive plasma sensors... not to mention would outright block a large swath of the sky... what if the target or Earth were in this swath? Further, if you need to use your engine or a high-power insturment (laser, radar) while you are eclipsed, then what? Batteries? There goes that 1kW per pound stuff... And with all that power from very small array at the center of the collector, you will substantial power handling equipment too. Oh and you can't use any inflatable or wire structure, which is what you would <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>have</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to use, to support any array cooling radiators. I figure such a power system would still weigh at or more than two hundred pounds, largely due to complex gimbaled mount (if one could be devised), power handling/batteries, and the relativly low-temperature array cooling systems.<br>
<br>
PLUS, you can use the reactor for other things too, like powering Lunar bases, Martian fuel factories, or Europan drilling rigs, all where a compact power source that doesn't need reliable sunlight or offers high radiation environment resistance <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>is a requirement, not an option.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
This would place the inflatable/wire collector option specific power only slightly better than Brayton-cycle nuclear, and with that long list of mechanical and electrical headaches that introduces substantial system risk compared to a ground-tested reactor, the choice is clear. Compact, proven, and reliable, the haulmark of nuclear power... three things large solar systems are not. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stevemick>SteveMick</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/28/04 4:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=209.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Nuclear vs. solar</span><hr size=1>  Wow! That was one of the most lame arguments on this subject I have ever heard and over many years I've heard quite a few!<br>
