<br>
Nuclear thermal is low Isp, and high mass flow rate in order to achieve high thrust.  The thrust may be applied like chemical propulsion systems, i.e. thrust for a few hours or days (depending on the mission and trajectory) and then &quot;coast&quot;.  Remember Apollo and how they would have a predetermined (relatively) short duration thrust to break orbit/make orbit either at Earth or Moon.<br>
<br>
The Nuclear Electric Systems have high Isp but use low thrust, however the thrust is applied for days, weeks, months or so on, again depending on mission and trajectory.<br>
<br>
The application is mission specific, but the bottom line is trying to achieve the highest possible specific energy and propulsive efficiency possible.  Therein lies the technical challenges to nuclear rocket designers.<br>
<br>
BTW - mission invovles key parameters such as origin, destination, payload and duration.  The faster one wants to travel (or conversely, the shorter the time) or the heavier the payload for a given mission duration, the greater the energy requirements.  Also, for any system Isp is tied to the available energy.<br>
<br>
An advantage of direct thrust - the propellant is used as the heat sink for the reactor - so no radiator.<br>
<br>
A closed nuclear electric system usually requires a radiator, however one can optimize the propellant flowrate and use the propellant as a partial heat sink.  As for radiators, their radiative effiency is roughly proportional to temperature (for a given emissivity).  It makes for an interesting problem to optimize efficiency (and therefore size) of a radiator against the thermodynamic efficiency of power system (where efficiency is related to the difference between the maximum and minimum temperatures of the energy conversion device - be it dynamic (e.g. turbine) or thermoelectric).  Think Carnot efficiency.  The minimum temperature of the power conversion system is constrained by the maximum desirable temperature of the radiator, barring other intermediate processes.  It's a really interesting and challenging (coupled non-linear equations).<br>
<br>
As for scalability - one can scale up a nuclear reactor and take advantage of &quot;self-shielding&quot;.  Small cores of high enrichment are a bit tricky to control, although modern electronics and instrumentation have greatly improved our capabilities in the last 3 decades. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=astronuc>Astronuc</A> at: 2/14/04 4:31 pm<br></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showPrevMessage?topicID=209.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showNextMessage?topicID=209.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=209.topic&index=20><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.emailToFriend?topicID=209.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.threadControl?topicID=209.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/space/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=209.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=209.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/unsubscr